{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"08a7fb88-f212-436a-af65-c7ab0eb8e4c5","content":"Here's a concise approach for tracing .NET 8 in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n**1. Get a shell into the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n**2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present):**\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**3. Find your process ID:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**4. Collect a CPU trace:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can copy out and analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n**To copy the trace off the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-nettrace> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**Alternatives if `dotnet-trace` can't be installed:**\n- **`dotnet-counters`** – lightweight; confirms CPU is from your app vs. GC, threadpool, etc.\n- **`dotnet-dump`** – grab a dump and inspect thread stacks for hot paths.\n- **Event Pipe via environment variables** – set `DOTNET_EnableEventPipe=1` and `DOTNET_EventPipeOutputPath=C:\\trace.nettrace` then restart the pod to collect without any tooling.\n\n> **Tip:** If the container lacks the .NET SDK, you can sidecar or `kubectl cp` a self-contained `dotnet-trace` binary into the pod instead of installing it.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"18be52af-10c1-42b1-8d41-94921f46044c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU. This is a troubleshooting/diagnostic question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":464,"requestId":"C89E:2D2CD9:1D33C9E:2053284:6A0524EE"},"id":"4c9a686d-6fcf-4c5d-9727-cda5622aa310","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:27:21.627Z","parentId":"c8006c48-db37-41fd-aed6-106fd4f58eb9"}
